{
  "doc_id": "55864",
  "text": "Here, we have used GLMMs applied to a dataset of infections with three common soil-transmitted helminths (STHs, i.e. Ascaris lumbricoides, Trichuris trichiura and hookworm) and self-reported fever in school-aged children from Zanzibar, Tanzania [CITATION_1] ; these data also included other potential infection risk factors (i.e. physical environment, demography, behaviour and socioeconomic status). GLMMs have previously been used to determine (or infer) the presence of both positive and negative interactions between parasites, in both simulated and wild animal parasite datasets [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . We used this integrated approach to investigate the role of co-infection in infection risk after accounting for other infection risk factors.",
